the boy's name   Vivian  , but now also rarely used for boys. This spelling was quite common in Old French. Its use as a girl's name in the English-speaking world was influenced by  Tennyson's  Merlin and Vivien (  1859 ). This name, from Arthurian legend, may represent an altered form of a Celtic name (perhaps akin to the Irish Gaelic name <i>Béibhinn</i> ‘white lady’, pronounced ‘bee-<b>veen</b>’). The actress  Vivien Leigh  (  1913–67 ) was christened <i>Vivian</i>."]},{"name":"Vyvyan","meanings":["Fanciful respelling of   Vivian ."]}]}],"historicEvents":[{"id":1705184,"age":6,"year":"1096","julianDay":2121366,"title":"The Crusades","description":"A series of religious wars between Christians and Muslims, known as the Crusades, occurred between 1096 and 1291, and played a large role in European Christian dominance in the Middle East.","url":"https://www.history.com/topics/middle-ages/crusades","urlTitle":"History - The Crusades","jurisdictionLevel":2},{"id":1705185,"age":16,"year":"1106","julianDay":2125018,"title":"The Battle of Tichebray","description":"King Henry I defeated and captured his brother, Robert of Normandy, at the Battle of Tinchebray in 1106. Robert remained in captivity until his death in 1134.","jurisdictionLevel":2}],"lifeSummary":"When Vivian De Gernet was born in 1090, in Lancaster, Lancashire, England, his father, Ralph de Garnet, was 32 and his mother, Bette Perrin, was 31. He married Emma Villiers in 1119, in Lancaster, Lancashire, England, United Kingdom. They were the parents of at least 2 sons and 1 daughter. His occupation is listed as 1st master forester of lancashire in Lancashire, England. He died in 1150, in Odell, Bedfordshire, England, at the age of 60."},"et":{"1090–1150":"1090–1150","1097–1155":"1097–1155","1110–1170":"1110–1170","1120–1189":"1120–1189","1140–1190":"1140–1190","1058–1093":"1058–1093","1060–1093":"1060–1093","1190":"1190","1090":"1090","1110":"1110","1120":"1120","1097":"1097","1140":"1140","1096":"1096","1150":